unished too', he whispers and gingerly shows you his back. Painful infected welts crisscross his back. 'I started to suffer these periodic attacks after my wife died. I thought it was my grief, but there is something more.' ö'She died in childbirth. Thoughts began to fill my head that she had been punished because the child was not mine. I felt it like it was a certainty, though that certainty has faded with time. I refused to bury her with honour, with her kinfolk.'         þ'Now I suspect that I was a fool. What will become of me?' He holds his head in self-pity. 'Where did you put her body?' you ask point blank. Quietly he draws you a map. He stands, a tranquil expression on his face. Without a word he stalks from the inn. The ground is too hard.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        >You unearth a small body, wrapped in a dark bloodstained robe.                                                                                                                                                                                                 ,Bury the woman's remains in the family plot?                                                                                                                                                                                                                   6You feel as though something has been lifted from you.                                                                                                                                                                                                         nThis small island is hallowed ground. Several tomb stones dot the land. A large family plot stands before you.                                                                                                                                 